producers of gun look-alikes, took sharp issue with the retailers' decision. 
Myron Shure, chairman, noted that retailers continue to sell other products, 
such as some interactive video games, that feature violence. Strombecker, which 
calls itself the nation's oldest toy company, produces such items as the 
American West silver-colored revolver under its Tootsie label. 
</P>
<P>
 "We are an easy target," Shure said. "They found an easy way to ease their 
conscience by eliminating a small part of the market." 
</P>
<P>
 However, Jerry Rubin, director of the anti-gun peace group called Los Angeles 
Alliance for Survival, said studies show that such play often leads to 
inordinate interest in real guns and to tragedy. But Rubin was also critical of 
Toys R Us and Kay-Bee.  
</P>
<P>
 "This is an inadequate solution to a dangerous situation," Rubin said. "A pink 
or green toy gun can be altered too. They should get rid of all toy guns." 
</P>
<P>
 But it won't be easy to wean some youngsters away. At Toys R Us and Kay-Bee 
stores in Bell Gardens on Friday, a full complement of real-looking toy guns 
was still on the shelves awaiting purchase. Maria Muro of Los Angeles bought 
her 6-year-old son, Billy Pulido, a silver six-shooter that -- in the dark -- 
might pass for a real handgun. 
</P>
<P>
 While he and playmates wrestled over the gun in the parking lot outside Toys R 
Us, his mother, 30, agreed it was better for her son not to play with toy guns 
and said she hoped his new toy wouldn't put him in danger. 
</P>
<P>
 But she added: "He likes guns. . . . If I take it away, he's going to be mad 
and cry." 
</P>
<P>
 Staff writers Lisa Respers and Errol Cockfield contributed to this report. 
