<HEADLINE>
<P>
FALCONS FALL AFTER SEEING MUIR TRAIL; FOOTBALL: CRESCENTA VALLEY TAKES LEAD ON 
95-YARD RUN BEFORE SUCCUMBING, 17-7. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By VINCE KOWALICK, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 In the long run, Chris Hedrick's 95-yard touchdown dash was about all 
Crescenta Valley High could muster in Friday night's 17-7 Pacific League loss 
to Muir at Pasadena City College. 
</P>
<P>
 Hedrick's burst up the middle gave Crescenta Valley a 7-0 first-quarter lead 
and raised hopes for the Falcons' first victory over Muir in 16 years. 
</P>
<P>
 But Muir (4-2, 1-0), despite five turnovers, pounded away with seven 
ballcarriers and piled up 365 yards while limiting Crescenta Valley to 100. 
</P>
<P>
 Even more impressive, the Mustangs played the second half without tailback 
Shaun Haslip, the team's leading rusher, who left in the second quarter with a 
sprained left ankle. 
</P>
<P>
 In Haslip's place, junior Charles Dunn rushed for a game-high 130 yards in six 
carries, including a 90-yard touchdown run in the third quarter that snapped a 
7-7 tie. 
</P>
<P>
 But for Crescenta Valley (5-1, 0-1), the inability to capitalize told the 
story. "They played defense," Falcon Coach Alan Eberhart said. 
</P>
<P>
 Muir sacked quarterback John Watts seven times for minus-48 yards, forcing two 
fumbles. Watts completed only four of 13 for 13 yards. 
</P>
<P>
 Hedrick, who scored his 15th touchdown of the season, finished with 126 yards 
in 14 carries. Hedrick's second-longest run went for eight yards. 
</P>
<P>
 "We tried our best," Hedrick said. "This is the level we want to play at." 
</P>
<P>
 Muir fumbled twice to end first-quarter drives. Haslip coughed up the ball at 
the Crescenta Valley 31-yard line on the Mustangs' opening drive and Mario 
Mendoza recovered. 
</P>
<P>
 Muir's second drive failed at the Falcon five-yard line when linebacker Rocky 
Barbaro stripped the ball from quarterback Jeremy Bonwell. That set the stage 
for Hedrick's 95-yard charge. 
</P>
<P>
 Muir evened the score early in the second quarter on a one-yard sneak by 
Bonwell. 
</P>
</TEXT>
