<HEADLINE>
<P>
HART PULLS AWAY FROM CANYON FOR 42-19 WIN 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By KENNEDY COSGROVE, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A 23-point victory over your archrival? 
</P>
<P>
 Not good enough for Hart High, ranked No. 1 in the region by The Times. 
</P>
<P>
 After defeating Canyon, 42-19, Friday night at Canyon before a crowd of 3,000, 
Hart players wore long faces and their coaches harped on their mistakes. 
</P>
<P>
 There were two fumbles, penalties, and mental mistakes on defense in the 
Foothill League opener. 
</P>
<P>
 "It was not a good effort by pretty much everybody tonight," said Hart's Ted 
Iacenda, who rushed for 129 yards and three touchdowns but fumbled in the 
fourth quarter. "I don't think I played well at all. 
</P>
<P>
 "It just goes to show how much we should have won by," he said. "I'm not 
saying that Canyon's not a good team, because they are, but I think we're that 
much better than them and we should have come out and dominated them the whole 
game." 
</P>
<P>
 Hart (6-0, 1-0) dominated in the second half, outscoring Canyon 21-6 to pull 
away from the Cowboys. 
</P>
<P>
 Canyon (1-4-1, 0-1) stayed with the high-powered Indians for two-plus 
quarters. But after closing to within 28-19 midway through the third quarter on 
Peter Gregory's five-yard scoring run, it was all Hart. 
</P>
<P>
 "We played hard," Canyon Coach Larry Mohr said. "That was the best football 
team we played all year." 
</P>
<P>
 Hart has won seven of the last eight meetings between the schools. 
</P>
<P>
 Canyon quarterback Ahjeron Palmer rushed for 134 yards in nine carries in the 
first half, darting through the Hart defense on plays designed for him. He 
finished with 160 yards in 16 carries. 
</P>
<P>
 Palmer's 29-yard touchdown jaunt with 3 minutes 5 seconds left in the first 
half pulled the Cowboys to within 14-13. Rick Engbrecht missed the extra-point 
attempt. 
</P>
<P>
 Hart scored on the subsequent drive on a six-yard run by quarterback Steve 
McKeon with 35 seconds remaining in the half. McKeon, a junior, completed 16 of 
24 passes for 252 yards and two touchdowns. 
</P>
<P>
 He suffered a headache and dizziness after the game and left in an ambulance 
to be checked for a concussion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
