<P>
TRIO SPARK ANTELOPE VALLEY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By GERRY PRICE 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 You might think Walker, Shrout and Lewis sounds like a good name for a law 
firm. But for the Antelope Valley High football team, they spelled the 
difference in a 20-6 victory over Burroughs in the Golden League opener for 
both teams Friday at Burroughs. 
</P>
<P>
 Sophomore defensive back Tony Walker was the first to make his presence felt. 
After Burroughs (3-3) had driven to the Antelope Valley five-yard line on the 
game's opening series, Walker dropped Burro running back DeMario Brown for 
back-to-back losses. A 28-yard field-goal attempt then failed. 
</P>
<P>
 Senior kicker Chad Shrout then booted a wind-aided 64-yard punt that pinned 
the Burros at their own six. A few minutes later, Shrout gave Antelope Valley 
(3-2) a 3-0 lead on a 37-yard field goal and added another with three seconds 
left before the half for a 6-0 cushion. 
</P>
<P>
 Jermaine Lewis, who averaged under 70 yards rushing going into the game, had 
121 yards in 23 carries and scored twice. GERRY PRICE 
</P>
